===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[fervour]] or [[tireless]] [[devotion]] for a person, cause, or ideal and determination in its furtherance; [[diligent]] [[enthusiasm]]; [[powerful]] [[interest]].
#: {{ux|en|She extols the virtues of veganism with missionary '''zeal'''.}}
#: {{syn|en|ardour|eagerness|enthusiasm|intensity|passion}}
#: {{ant|en|apathy}}
#* '''1611''', ''{{w|King James Version}} of the {{w|Bible}},'' {{w|Epistle to the Romans|Romans}} 10.2,<sup>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Romans+10&version=KJV]</sup>
#*: {{...}} I bear them record that they have a '''zeal''' of God, but not according to knowledge.
#* '''1687''', {{w|John Dryden}}, ''{{w|The Hind and the Panther}},'' London: Jacob Tonson, Part{{nbsp}}3, p.{{nbsp}}96,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A36627.0001.001]</sup>
#*: '''Zeal''', the blind conductor of the will
#* '''1779''', {{w|David Hume}}, ''{{w|Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion}},'' Part{{nbsp}}12, pp.{{nbsp}}143-144,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004895521.0001.000]</sup>
#*: {{...}} the highest '''zeal'''  in religion and the deepest hypocrisy, so far from being inconsistent, are often or commonly united in the same individual character.
#* '''1815''', {{w|Jane Austen}}, ''{{w|Emma (novel)|Emma}},'' London: John Murray, Volume{{nbsp}}1, Chapter{{nbsp}}14, p.{{nbsp}}250,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/emmanovelinthree131aust/page/n257]</sup>
#*: [He] would begin admiring her drawings with so much '''zeal''' and so little knowledge as seemed terribly like a would-be lover,
#* '''1962''', {{w|Rachel Carson}}, ''{{w|Silent Spring}},'' Boston: Houghton Mifflin, Chapter{{nbsp}}15, p.{{nbsp}}248,<sup>[https://www.fadedpage.com/books/20151002/html.php]</sup>
#*: The stockman’s '''zeal''' for eliminating the coyote has resulted in plagues of field mice, which the coyote formerly controlled.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A person who [[exhibit]]s such fervour or tireless devotion.
#: {{syn|en|zealot}}
#* '''1614''', {{w|Ben Jonson}}, ''{{w|Bartholomew Fair (play)|Bartholomew Fair}},'' London: Robert Allot, Act{{nbsp}}V, Scene{{nbsp}}5, p.{{nbsp}}85,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/A04633.0001.001]</sup>
